values.studentResponsFeedback: Michelle states that she integrates teaching consistently throughout each day. She allows Paige to have autonomy working with patients whom she is comfortable. She prioritizes graded exposure and responsibility as well as opportunities to collaborate in the moment. They take tie to debrief after each patient, at lunch or the end of the day depending on the flow of the day and where their discussions fit. Paige consistently asks questions to understand her CI's thought process.
values.studentDocSkills: The focus for the remainder of the clinical experience will be confidence, and voice projection. Michelle shares a story of Paige working with a patient who was hard of hearing which left no option but voice projection.  Paige will also take on the majority of the responsibility for the initial examination consults in the clinic for the remainder of the clinical experience.
values.quesRegardingCIET: Curricular weaknesses include a student's ability to come into an initial examination and utilize the information gathered during the subjective interview/ history to guide prioritization of exam components. Students come in with a lot of knowledge however the challenge becomes having an awareness of not needing to complete everything/ the entire exam sequence from start to finish on every patient but that it is okay to “go off the beaten path.”
values.suggestionsForClinicalteam: The 1-hour treatment sessions allow Paige to take her time to focus on the quality of what she is doing. For documentation, they don't have to do point of service notes, so they are able to focus on the content of the examination, streamlining and practicing skills. Michelle notes that she appreciates the conciseness of the CIET compared to the CPI tool.
